        ],
        [
          "Classification",
          "Higher Education",
          "E-Learning",
          "Final Mark in a Course",
          "Pass (0) vs Fail (1)",
          "32593",
          "7 courses in OULAD",
          "VLE logs",
          "Sum of Clicks per activity type.",
          "Every Week (Week 0 to Week 41)",
          "Each activity type was aggregated from the start to current week (in this case, there are 20 activity types, so each model has 20 features representing the number of clicks in each activity.\n\nData was oversampled using SMOTE and Standardized (I’m guessing this is what StandardNormalization.\n\n\n\n",
          "DT\nLogistic Regression\nGaussianNB\nKNN\nLDA\nSVM\nAdaBoost\nBagging\nExtraTrees\nRandom Forest\nXGBoost\nMLP",
          "10-Fold Cross-Validation",
          "{Accuracy: 0.79 - Random Forest & ExtraTrees, Mean Rank: 10.04 - Random Forest}",
          "In total, the authors created 10824 models, one per course iteration and Week.\n\nAuthors publish results in terms of Accuracy, Mean Rank  and Friedman’s test. Most of the results shown are averaged out over the full period or aggregated by some week thresholds (Week 10, Week 20, Week 30, Week 40).\n\nAt a second level of analysis, the authors look to distinguish differences in Predictive capabilities between STEM and Social Science Courses and find that the models in STEM achieve better scores than the ones for SS. \n\nRecommendation of authors is to perform early prediction for STEM at Week 10 and for SS at week 20.\n\n\n\n",
          "Each model is course-specific, making it impractical for implementation.\n\nNo analysis of casuses for difference in performance between STEM and SS. \n\nAccuracy is the only model performance metric considered."
        ]
      ],
      "index": 4
    }
  ],
